uch as mobile clinics on wheels; pop-up clinics in repurposed spaces; and unlicensed, makeshift clinics run by health activists. Despite their unassuming appearances, these clinics are vital resources for marginalized populations that often go unnoticed by the general public, revealing the shortcomings of our formal health care system.By examining these alternative health care spaces, the authors expose the inequities entrenched in the broader health care system and urge a reevaluation of it entirely in order to address these injustices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHealth services accessibilityzUnited States2DLC. 0aImmigrantsxHealth and hygienezUnited States2DLC. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carezUnited States2DLC. 0aMedical policyzUnited States2DLC. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  aAffordable Care Act.  aAmerica health care system.  aAmerican healthcare.  aCatholic Worker Movement.  aDisability and immigration.  aFree clinic.  aHarris Health System.  aHealth care coverage.  aHealth equity.  aImmigrant health care.  aMigrant Health Care.  aSafety Net.  aUniversal health care.  ahealth disparities.  ahealthcare and immigrants.  ahealthcare and immigration.  ahealthcare system.  aimmigrants and health insurance.  asystem of health care.  aundocumented immigrants and health care, uninsured migrants.1 aHoekstra, Erin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJimenez, Anthony M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479821594.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479821594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479821594/original  a978-3-